\begin_layout Subsubsection
LDAP
\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
LDAP
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
ASM can also use an LDAP server to authenticate your users.
 ASM will prompt for a username and password on startup and will then search
 the LDAP tree for an entry matching the username entered.
 If it finds one, it will then attempt to bind to the tree as that user,
 using the password supplied.
 As ever, a matching ASM user must exist in the database.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The LDAP fields asm needs are:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
LDAP URL
\series default
: This is the URL to the ldap server, typically something like ldap://server/,
 you can supply a port as normal (eg: If you have an ActiveDirectory domain
 you'd like to use for authentication on port 3268 - ldap://server:3268/).
 You can also use ldaps:// for SSL enabled LDAP connections.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
LDAP User
\series default
: The DN of a user allowed to conduct searches of the LDAP tree.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
LDAP Password
\series default
: The password for the user allowed to conduct searches of the LDAP tree.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
LDAP DN
\series default
: The base DN to conduct searches from when looking for users - eg: ou=Users,dc=
example,dc=com
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
LDAP Filter
\series default
: The search filter to use when locating users.
 The {0} token will be replaced by the username the user enters when attempting
 to login.
 For example, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

(cn={0})
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, to locate a user with a cn matching the username.
 ActiveDirectory users should use 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

(sAMAccountName={0})
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
WARNING: If you supply an LDAP URL and don't have an LDAP server, you will
 not be able to log in to ASM.

\series default
 You can clear LDAP settings by opening a SQL tool on your database and
 running 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

DELETE FROM configuration WHERE ItemName Like 'LDAP%';
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

